To find the rank of the matrix A, we need to perform Gaussian elimination to transform the matrix into its row-echelon form and then count the number of non-zero rows.

Matrix A:
\begin{pmatrix}
3 & -2 & 6 \\
-2 & 2 & -4 \\
1 & -1 & 2
\end{pmatrix}

Step 1: Add 2/3 times the first row to the second row to eliminate the first element in the second row.

\begin{pmatrix}
3 & -2 & 6 \\
0 & 4/3 & -4 \\
1 & -1 & 2
\end{pmatrix}

Step 2: Subtract 1/3 times the first row from the third row to eliminate the first element in the third row.

\begin{pmatrix}
3 & -2 & 6 \\
0 & 4/3 & -4 \\
0 & -1/3 & 0
\end{pmatrix}

Step 3: Multiply the second row by 3/4 to make the second element in the second row equal to 1.

\begin{pmatrix}
3 & -2 & 6 \\
0 & 1 & -3 \\
0 & -1/3 & 0
\end{pmatrix}

Step 4: Add 1/3 times the second row to the third row to eliminate the second element in the third row.

\begin{pmatrix}
3 & -2 & 6 \\
0 & 1 & -3 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}

Now the matrix is in row-echelon form. We can see that there are 3 non-zero rows, so the rank of the matrix A is 3.
